1.body: Create a Pop!_OS Live USB - Create a bootable live USB using Etcher, Popsicle, or Rufus. Install Pop!_OS - Specify locale settings, encrypt the system drive, and create a user account.
1.title: Getting Started

10.body: Linux Download ISO Download the appropriate Pop!_OS.iso file for your target system. See the preparation guide for information about each version. Take note of the hash value for your chosen ISO. Use this value to verify the integrity of the ISO file in step four of the installation process. Compare Hash Values
10.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Using Linux » Download the Pop!_OS.iso File
10.title: Download the Pop!_OS.iso File

11.body: Flash your USB media with the Pop!_OS.iso image. Note that this process will completely erase all previous data on the USB storage device. Launch Popsicle. The app may display as USB Flasher in search results. Choose Image Click Choose Image. Launch Popsicle Navigate to the local directory with your Pop!_OS.iso file and select it. Find Image Click the drop down menu next to Hash and choose SHA256, then click Check. Compare the hash result to the value you saw when selecting your Pop!_OS.iso file. Verify ISO Click Next. Select the USB installation media. Click Next. Select Media Enter your system password if prompted, then wait for the installation to complete. Flashing Process Click Done when the process completes.
11.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Using Linux » Create the Bootable USB
11.title: Create the Bootable USB

12.body: Use your bootable Pop!_OS USB to demo, install, or recover a current Pop!_OS installation.
12.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Using Linux » Next Steps
12.title: Next Steps

13.body: Power off the target computer and insert the bootable USB. Power on the computer and enter the boot device menu selection for your BIOS or UEFI system. Follow the steps in the Standard Installation section.
13.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Using Linux » Install Pop!_OS
13.title: Install Pop!_OS

14.body: Use the bootable USB to demo Pop!_OS as a live system.
14.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Using Linux » Demo Pop!_OS
14.title: Demo Pop!_OS

15.body: The Pop!_OS installer guides the user through setup of basic system settings. Verify system and installation requirements. Choose a locale and keyboard language. Perform system hard drive selection and partitioning (advanced). Create a user account. Enable system disk encryptions.
15.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Standard Installation » Installing Pop!_OS
15.title: Installing Pop!_OS

17.body: Component Requirement Recommended CPU 64-bit x86 architecture RAM 2 GB 4 GB Drive Storage 20 GB
17.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Standard Installation » System Specifications
17.title: System Specifications

18.body: Systems with Secure Boot enabled must disable this feature before installing Pop!_OS. Secure boot can be disabled in the BIOS of most computers; however, the process to disable secure boot will vary by laptop and motherboard model.
18.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Standard Installation » Secure Boot
18.title: Secure Boot

19.body: The Pop!_OS.iso can be easily flashed to a USB drive. See Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB.
19.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Standard Installation » Installation Media
19.title: Installation Media

2.body: Pop!_OS can be run from a USB drive in a live environment. You can use the live USB to install Pop!_OS permenantly on a system, demo Pop!_OS without installing, or use the drive as a system recovery tool.
2.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Create Pop!_OS Installation Media
2.title: Create Pop!_OS Installation Media

20.body: Choose a language. Choose Language Select a locale. Language Region Select a keyboard input language. Keyboard Language Select a keyboard layout. Keyboard Layout Choose the Clean Install option for a standard installation. This is the best option for new Linux users, but be aware that this will erase all contents of the target drive. Note : The Custom (Advanced) option opens GParted. GParted allows users to choose partition tables and create custom partitions, among other options. Clean Install Choose the target drive for the OS installation. Click Erase and Install. Select Drive Enter your first and last name (or a display name). A suggested username will populate in the User Name field. Tip : You don't need to type your username when logging into Pop!_OS normally, but it can be handy to remember when logging into a terminal session, logging in remotely via SSH, or performing certain configurations. Enter Username Enter the account password. Enter Password Choose to encrypt the drive, and optionally create a separate encryption password. Note : Encrypting the system disk ensures user data is secure in the event that someone gains unauthorized physical access to the device. Encrypt Drive Wait for the installation to complete. Click Restart Device when prompted. Restart System
20.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Standard Installation » Pop!_OS Installation
20.title: Pop!_OS Installation

3.body: Creating a bootable Pop!_OS USB drive requires three components: A USB flash drive. The flash drive must have at least 8 GB of free space. All data on the flash drive will be lost during the creation process. The Pop!_OS.iso image: Download Pop!_OS at this link. A program to write the Pop!_OS.iso image to the flash drive. Reference the table below for popular image flashing software. Program OS Compatibility Etcher Windows, macOS, Linux Popsicle Linux Rufus Windows
3.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Preparation
3.title: Preparation

4.body: Pop!_OS offers its ISO image in 3 varieties: Intel/AMD - An ISO that does not include propriety NVIDIA drivers. Note : If you accidentally install the non-NVIDIA version on a PC with a discrete NVIDIA GPU, run sudo apt install system76-driver-nvidia in a Terminal session to obtain the missing drivers. NVIDIA - An ISO containing proprietary NVIDIA drivers for systems with discrete NVIDIA GPUs. RAS PI 4 - An ISO image compatible with the ARM64 processor in a Raspberry Pi 4.
4.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Choose a Pop!_OS Image
4.title: Choose a Pop!_OS Image

5.body: This process will vary depending on the host operating system. Refer to the appropriate page for your current operating system. Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB in Linux
5.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Create the Installation Media
5.title: Create the Installation Media

6.body: This section explains the process of creating a bootable Pop!_OS USB in Linux using Popsicle. Install ISO flashing software. Download the Pop!_OS.iso file. Flash the ISO to your USB storage device.
6.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Using Linux » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB in Linux
6.title: Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB in Linux

7.body: Popsicle is a Linux utility for flashing multiple USB devices at once. You can install Popsicle as an AppImage or a Flatpak.
7.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Using Linux » Install Popsicle
7.title: Install Popsicle

8.body: Download the Popsicle AppImage from this Popsicle repository. Navigate to the downloaded AppImage. Right-click the AppImage and select Properties. Select the Permissions tab and check the Execute box. AppImage Execute Permission Double click the Popsicle AppImage to launch it.
8.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Using Linux » AppImage
8.title: AppImage

9.body: Follow the instructions on Flatpak.org if Flatpak is not installed in your Linux distribution. Open a Terminal session and enter this command: flatpak install flathub com.system76.Popsicle Enter this command to launch Popsicle: flatpak run com.system76.Popsicle
9.breadcrumbs: Getting Started » Create a Bootable Pop!_OS USB Device » Using Linux » Flatpak
9.title: Flatpak
